0 172.16.0.3/31 (to super), eth1 172.16.0.8/31 (to leaf0), eth2 172.16.0.10/31 (to leaf1) — all UP.\n- leaf_router_0_0\n  - eth0 172.16.0.5/31 (to spine0), eth1 172.16.0.9/31 (to spine1), eth2 10.0.0.1/24 (to pc_0_0) — eth2 UP.\n- leaf_router_0_1\n  - eth0 172.16.0.7/31 (to spine0), eth1 172.16.0.11/31 (to spine1), eth2 10.0.1.1/24 (to pc_0_1) — eth2 UP.\n\n2) BGP control-plane (summaries from radios)\n- leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200)\n  - BGP table shows 10.0.0.0/24 as local (i), and 10.0.1.0/24 reachable via nexthops 172.16.0.4 and 172.16.0.8 (i.e., paths via the two spines).\n- leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201)\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 local; 10.0.0.0/24 via nexthops 172.16.0.6 and 172.16.0.10.\n- spine_router_0_0 (AS 65100) and spine_router_0_1 (AS 65101)\n  - Both spines show learned routes to the leaf /24s. Multiple paths are present where expected (via direct leaf and via super-spine aggregated path).\n- super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000)\n  - Learns both host prefixes via spines; shows the two spine nexthops for each prefix.\n\nInterpretation: BGP prefix propagation is consistent and symmetric — each leaf advertises its /24 and the rest of the fabric has routes to both /24s with expected nexthops.\n\n3) Routing (RIB/FIB) and forwarding nexthops\n- leaf_router_0_0 route to 10.0.1.0/24 → via 172.16.0.4 (spine_router_0_0)\n- leaf_router_0_1 route to 10.0.0.0/24 → via 172.16.0.6 (spine_router_0_0)\n- spine_router_0_0 has direct next-hops to both leaves for the two /24s (via eth1 and eth2 respectively).\n- super_spine_router_0 chosen next-hop for both /24s is spine_router_0_0 (172.16.0.1) in the current selection.\n\nThese routes form reasonable forwarding paths in a Clos (traffic can flow leaf→spine→leaf, and reverse paths mirror via the same spine).\n\n4) Host-side observations\n- pc_0_0 (sampled): eth0 10.0.0.2/24, default gw 10.0.0.1. Interface is UP but packet counters are zero (RX 0 TX 0).\n- leaf_router_0_0 eth2 (10.0.0.1/24) shows zero RX/TX packets on that interface — matching pc_0_0 counters (suggests no host-originated traffic during probe).\n- Attempt to retrieve pc_0_1 configuration failed due to environment/tool error (container exec conflict).\n\nAnomalies and abnormal behavior\n1) Tool/environment collection failures\n- Several collection operations (get_reachability, some get_host_net_config calls, ping_pair tests) failed with: \"container ... is not running\" / exec conflict. This prevented active reachability tests and retrieving pc_0_1 host config.\n  - Impact: inability to run live pings between hosts from the probe harness, and missing complete host-side state for pc_0_1.\n\n2) Host-to-leaf edge traffic counters are zero\n- Observed zero traffic on pc_0_0 (RX/TX packets = 0) and corresponding leaf_router_0_0 eth2 shows zero RX/TX. Same pattern for leaf_router_0_1 eth2 (no RX/TX), although pc_0_1 could not be queried.\n  - Possible interpretations: hosts are idle and not initiating traffic during tests; or host-to-leaf link is up but hosts are down/paused; or probing pings were not executed because of the test environment failure.\n  - Note: router-to-router links show packet counters non-zero (they have small RX/TX counts), indicating routing plane traffic exists but host-facing interfaces show no traffic.\n\n3) No routing/BGP anomalies detected\n- No evidence of BGP session flap or route withdrawal: BGP tables across devices show expected prefixes and multiple paths. Routing table entries correspond to BGP next-hops and connected /31s. No route loops or null next-hops observed in the collected outputs.\n\nLocalization — where the issues are (ranking)\n- Primary problem source (non-network): probe environment / container execution. This impacted ability to exercise data-plane tests (pings) and to collect pc_0_1 config. Evidence: “container ... is not running” errors from tool outputs.\n- Observed network-local symptom: host-facing interfaces (leaf eth2 and pc eth0) show zero packet counters. Localization: edges (pc_0_0 and leaf_router_0_0 eth2; likewise for pc_0_1/leaf_router_0_1) — either hosts not sending traffic or host-side/process issue. Routers and inter-router fabric appear healthy.\n- Routers (super_spine_router_0, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1): BGP/routing tables and inter-router interface state show no anomaly.\n\nRoot-cause analysis (most-likely causes from available evidence)\n1) Environment/tool failure\n- The container/execution error prevented running active tests and collecting pc_0_1 state. Root cause for missing active pings and missing host data is the probe environment (container/process not running). This is verified by explicit error messages returned by the tooling.\n\n2) Host-edge quiescence\n- The zero packet counters on host-facing interfaces (both pc and leaf-facing interfaces) are consistent with hosts being idle or virtual host processes being stopped/paused. Because the router side shows the interface UP with correct IPs, the link layer is up; the absence of packets indicates lack of host-originated traffic. Without a successful ping test (blocked by tool error), we cannot distinguish “host not running” from “packets dropped immediately by leaf” — however the router logs/packet counters on inter-router links show activity, and leaf->spine counters are non-zero, which points away from fabric-wide drops and toward host-side inactivity.\n\n3) No evidence of protocol-level root cause inside fabric\n- BGP distribution and selection look normal. No evidence of misconfiguration that causes route leaks, missing prefixes, or forwarding loops in the collected outputs. Thus there is no observable root cause inside the router fabric for loss of host-to-host connectivity.\n\nData collection gaps / limitations\n- Cannot confirm host-to-host ICMP/test traffic because ping_pair executions failed (container not running).\n- pc_0_1 network config was not obtained (tool error). This prevents confirming pc_0_1 IP/gateway and interface counters.\n- No FRR \"show ip bgp summary\" or BGP session status outputs were collected beyond the route table excerpts; however the presence of learned prefixes suggests sessions are established.\n\nConclusion\n- Fabric control-plane: healthy and converged (BGP routes for both host prefixes present on all routers; inter-router links up).\n- Fabric forwarding: routes and nexthops are consistent and form plausible symmetric forwarding paths (leaf ↔ spine ↔ leaf).\n- Observed anomaly: no host-side traffic seen on host-facing interfaces; active host reachability tests could not be run due to the environment/tool error (container not running). This localizes the immediate problem to the probe environment and/or the host endpoints (pc_0_0 and pc_0_1) rather than to spine/super-spine/router BGP forwarding.\n- Required follow-ups to complete diagnosis (not mitigation): re-run the host-level probes after starting the probe container/process, collect pc_0_1 info, run ICMP tests between hosts, and collect FRR BGP session summaries if any inter-router session logs show intermittent state changes.\n\n(End of report), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.\nAI: \nTool: [\"dns_record_error\", \"host_crash\", \"host_ip_conflict\", \"host_incorrect_dns\", \"host_incorrect_gateway\", \"host_incorrect_ip\", \"host_incorrect_netmask\", \"host_missing_ip\", \"dhcp_service_down\", \"dns_service_down\", \"host_vpn_membership_missing\", \"link_detach\", \"link_down\", \"link_flap\", \"link_fragmentation_disabled\", \"arp_acl_block\", \"bgp_acl_block\", \"dns_port_blocked\", \"http_acl_block\", \"icmp_acl_block\", \"ospf_acl_block\", \"bgp_asn_misconfig\", \"bgp_blackhole_route_leak\", \"bgp_hijacking\", \"bgp_missing_route_advertisement\", \"host_static_blackhole\", \"dhcp_missing_subnet\", \"mac_address_conflict\", \"ospf_area_misconfiguration\", \"ospf_neighbor_missing\", \"p4_aggressive_detection_thresholds\", \"flow_rule_loop\", \"flow_rule_shadowing\", 